cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Okay, first of all today we're going to look at Major Suit openings of 1@h and 1@s and how Asking Bids tie in with those.

We have covered these to some extent over previous months, but now we can nail these sequences down completely: So first we come to Major Suit sequences where Responder bids 1NT with a game-going hand which contains primary support for Opener's major.

If we are using Asking Bids then the "long-weak suit" variety of response goes out of the window (unless responder a passed hand) and then after the Forcing 1NT response and Openers subsequent bid of their 2nd suit...   

...a bid in the        cheapest  NEW   suit is ^*bGamma^*n in Opener's major.
...a bid in the ^*b 2nd ^*n cheapest NEW suit is ^*bGamma^*n in Opener's 2nd suit   OR   as ^*b BETA ^*n if no 2nd suit shown.
^c@2
1@h  -  1NT  -  2@c  -  2@d(Gamma in @h)
1@s  -  1NT  -  2@c  -  2@d(Gamma in @s)
1@h  -  1NT  -  2@c  -  2@s(Gamma in @c)
1@s  -  1NT  -  2@c  -  2@h(Gamma in @c)

1@h  -  1NT  -  2@d  -  2@s(Gamma in @h)       
1@s  -  1NT  -  2@d  -  2@h(Gamma in @s)
1@h  -  1NT  -  2@d  -  2@s(Gamma in @d)
1@s  -  1NT  -  2@d  -  2@h(Gamma in @d)

1@h  -  1NT  -  2@h  -  2@s(Gamma in @h)
1@h  -  1NT  -  2@h  -  3@c(Beta)                   ^l as  @c's   is  2nd cheapest suit and no 2nd suit shown by Opener

1@h  -  1NT  -  2@s  -  3@c(Gamma in @h)
1@s  -  1NT  -  2@s  -  3@d(Beta)                   ^l as  @d's   is  2nd cheapest suit and no 2nd suit shown by Opener
|n#|5|at|   ...etc...|
