fp|t-title|at|After the 2@c  Opening|fp||at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Next we come to the 2@c Openings.

Here immediate jump-shifts by Responder are Alpha in the suit bid, but there are other ways by which we can get into a full-blown Asking Bid sequence:    Firstly, after
 
^c@22@c  -  2@d  -  2@h/@s,   a bid at the 3  -  level in the OTHER Major is Eta in Opener's Major.

2@c  -  2@d  -  2@h  -  3@s  ^j is  Eta in @h's    ^o(almost identical in a way to the 
2@c  -  2@d  -  2@s  -  3@h  ^j is  Eta in @s's    ^o Stayman sequences on the previous page).

^j@2In both of these cases Relay Beta is available over the Eta Response and Epsilons are also available.
^b@2Secondly, after 
^c@2
2@c  -  2@d  -  2@h/@s  -  4@c  ^j @2the bid of 4@c is a ^*b length known ^*n Gamma in @c's (because with 4-6+, the 3@c Opening would have been used).        Similarly after 
^c@2
2@c  -  2@d  -  3@c      -  4@c ^j and 
2@c  -  2@d  -  2NT    -  4@c^j the immediate bid of 4@c is Gamma in @c's with a 6 card minimum length.
^b@2
It is true, that with  3406  or  4306,  Opener STILL uses the 2@c Opening, but these hand-types are pretty rare.

^b@2At the end of the day, it's a matter of partnership agreement  whether you use a length-known or length unknown Gamma with the

^c2@c  -  2@d  -  2@h/@s  -  4@c 

sequence.|
