nt|^z   @3^b@2|at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|After the 3@c  Opening|fp||at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Next we come to 3@c.

Over 3@c, 3@h and 3@s show slam interest in that suit.

Now Opener relays in the next bid up
 
^c3@c  -  3@h  -  3@s  ^h@2@{  to show 4-cards in the OTHER Major (Responder is more likely
^c3@c  -  3@s  -  3NT  ^h@2@{  to bid 3@d if they have slam interest in EITHER Major).

^b@2Now  4@c  by responder is Gamma in Clubs.

^c3@c  -  3@h  -  3@s    -  4@c(Gamma in @c's)
^c3@c  -  3@s  -  3NT  -  4@c(Gamma in @c's)

If Opener by-passes the bid above relay then these are ETA Responses for the Major that Responder just bid, promising a 4-card holding in that suit.    So

^c3@c   -   3@h   -   4@d(Eta Response)       showing two top honours in @h's without the Jack.

Now a relay over the response is Relay Beta and asking bids are established so Epsilons are permitted.

Needless to say, with length and strength in BOTH Majors, Responder normally does better to bid 3@d over 3@c to find out which Major Opener has, and then 4@d (Beta) over Opener's Rebid.

This implicitly agrees the Major Opener has shown, and so Epsilons can be used over the Beta Response.

Any questions on Asks over a 3@c Opening? |
