nt|^z   @3^b@2|at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|After the Multi-style 2NT Opening         |fp||at|continued^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  The other sequence where Asking Bids come into our methods is after the sequence 
^c@2
2NT  -  4@c ^hshowing a strong distributional hand and forcing Opener to clarify their hand-type: After 
^c
2NT  -  4@c   -   4@d(Majors)    -    ??,        now  4NT  is Gamma in Hearts and  5@c  is Gamma in Spades.

^bIn each case Asking Bids are now established and so Relay Beta and Epsilons follow.   After 

2NT  -  4@c   -   4@h(Minors)    -     ??,       @2now  4@s  is Gamma in @c's and 4NT is Gamma in @d's and 
     as above, Asking Bids are now established.
^b@2
When, however, Opener shows long @c's (2NT - 4@c - 4NT) all continuations are strictly natural and no Asking Bids are allowed.

One last thing in relation to Major 2-suiters is the effect the 2NT Opening has on Asking Bids after sequences such as 

^c1@s  -  1NT  -  3@h

Because  5-5 Major 2 suiters are opened with 2NT, and that sequence promises AT LEAST 5-5, it follows that that sequence is promising at least 6-5 distribution.

The minimum length for a Gamma in either Major has to be amended accordingly, so 

^c1@s  -  1NT  -  3@h  -  4@c        here the  4@c   bid is Gamma in @s, with a ^*b minimum length of 6 cards^*n.|
